Research Question¶

For our research question, we will be investigating potential factors that could influence a movie’s IMDb score. This topic is interesting because the opinion of viewers of movies may vary based on a plethora of factors. The length of the movie, the language the movie is in, genre, the number of people that viewed it, and the number of people that reviewed it all may affect a movie’s score. It is interesting to see reviews of movies and wonder why some rate better than others; using a regression, we can see which variables have more weight on the score, and we can analyze why that may be the case.

Context¶

The “world” where this would happen is the world of movie reviews, but in this case it is regular citizens, not licensed movie critics, that offer their opinions. Movie critics could be included and offer their opinion, but the website is open to the public to offer a review, so more regular people have the chance to review movies and give them scores. Because many of the movies are American movies in English, the “world” may include more English-speakers than non-English speakers, however there are still a plethora of other languages and countries. This “world” would affect anyone who watches and likes movies.

Relevance¶

These findings are relevant to consumers who are planning to purchase movies, directors trying to make movies that people like, actors who are trying to make money acting and therefore also interested in what factors make people like movies, and finally anyone interested to see what affects movie scores. For consumers, they can determine if a movie is worth their money by viewing its score, but it would be more beneficial to them to know which factors influence the score. For example, if they don't mind a longer movie but our regression shows that most people rate longer movies lower, that specific consumer can determine if their demand may be different than most people. Directors and actors can see what factors affect a score and possibly align their future films with these factors to see if they can make more money. Finally, the general public can simply see how certain movies are rated based on which factors.

Supporting Evidence¶

To prove why our topic and research question is relevant, we found a study on the effect movie reviews have on consumers. Jacob R. Pentheny, a PHD student asked the question: “Can online word-of-mouth such as professional reviews by critics and comments and descriptive reviews by consumers positively or negatively affect an individual consumer’s decision to purchase a movie ticket?" (Pentheny, 2). His findings showed that reviews do in fact have an effect on consumers, which again proves why what affects a review is important per our research question. Another research paper by Robert O. Wyatt and David P. Badger asked: "can a critical review stimulate or discourage audience interest in attending a particular film, and can a review significantly affect the audience's evaluation of a film afterwards?" (Wyatt, 1). Wyatt and Badger found that critical reviews do in fact have statistical significance in determining how an audience feels about the film. This means that our research question is important because we are looking into what affects those reviews, and based on their evidence, that review could mean something in terms of how well a movie does for the effect of these reviews. A third study researched "Quantitative approaches for evaluating the influence of films using the IMDb database" which is extremely relevant to our question because they specifically look at the IMBd database (Canet, 1). Fernando J Canet looks into the most influential movies of all time and determines what about those movies made them influencial. Reviews of the most influencial movies are bound to play a role in their influence, and our analysis can offer background information on what makes a review better or worse that could then influence the movie's popularity. These studies offer background information that reviews do in fact affect film attendance and how much the audience likes the film, and we know intuitively, this will affect economic sales. Our research question will add to existing literature about what exactly affects a review. As for hypothesizing different regressors and what effect they will have on the imdb score, the table below includes more supporting evidence.

Data¶

Our data includes movie reviews that range from the 1980s to 2016. There are categorical and numerical variables. Our dataset is quite large, with over 5,000 movies entered. Some interesting features are that a lot of the movies entered are blockbuster movies and popular actors and actresses dominate the movies on the list. We are also interested to see whether IMDb score is correlated with duration, number of voted users, and number user for reviews. Below we have included a table describing each variable we will use in our regression and a hypothesis on how that variable will affect the IMDb score.

General Data Description and Economic Hypothesis¶

Variables Description Economic Hypothesis
Duration This is the duration of the movie, in minutes. It is listed as an integer We hypothesize that duration will have a negative effect. We live in a society where everyone lives a fast-paced life, so they crave quick entertainment. A longer duration of a movie would create a lower score of the movie rating.
Genre This is the genre of the movie. It is a dummy variable with documentary = 1 and all other types of genre = 0. We hypothesize that genre will have a positive effect due to the fact that it is a dummy variable with documentary =1 and people usually rate documentaries higher. They are seen as educational, high-quality films, and viewers tend to enjoy them more because they find them more realistic because they are based in reality. Using supporting evidence, we found that "documentary has become the flagship for a cinema of social engagement and distinctive vision (Nichols, 1). This means that the documentary has become an important part of the film industry, and users tend to like documentaries.
Number of voted users This is the number of users who rated the movie. We hypothesize that the number of users who vote on the movie rating will create a negative effect. We are assuming that the reason people rate a movie is to explain why they did not like it.
Number of users for reviews This is the number of users who wrote out a review for the movie. It is distinct from the number of users that voted because the voters only rated the movie on a 1-10 scale. The reviewers wrote out an actual review of the movie. This is a more time-intensive activity, which is demonstrated in the lower number of reviews compared to ratings for each movie. We hypothesize that the number of users who wrote reviews will create a negative effect, for the same reasons as number of users who vote in general will create a negative effect.
Language This is the language that the movie is in. It is a dummy variable with English = 1 and other languages = 0. We hypothesize that the movie being in English will create a positive effect becasue the imbd website is in English and many of the movies are, so just based on higher numbers, English movies are bound to get higher reviews.
Country This is the country that movie was made in. It is a dummy variable with the movie being made in USA = 1 and other = 0. We hypothesize that the movie being made in the USA would create a positive effect because there is a lot of funding in the film industry. We found that according to a 2013 survey by Consumer Reports National Research Center, 78 percent of Americans preferred to buy a product made in the USA over one made in a different country (Handlin). 78% is a large majority, so our hypothesis stands. There is also some bias that movies and things in general made in the USA are inherently better.

Testing for Assumptions (ex. OVB, Multicollinearity, Heteroskedasticity)¶

Omitted Variable Bias¶

We are constrained by the limits of our dataset. There are not many quantitative variables that we have in use for our analysis. We do have complete data on the quantitative independent variables in our possession, which are: duration, number of written reviews, and number of votes.

Though there may be other quantitative variables that could affect a movie's IMDB rating (ex: # of years experience for lead actor), these are not contained within our dataset, and there is no way to account for it. Still, it is good to keep in mind the limitations of our dataset and discuss it when talking about our final results

Multicollinearity¶

If multicollinearity fails between variables, then one of the variables must be taken out. Multicollinearity is an assuption where one variable cannot be a linear transformation of another variable. The only two variables that would even need to be tested for this are between "number of written reviews" and "number of votes". Though I am sure that these variables are correlated (and even highly so), all we need to ensure is that one is not a linear transformation of the other.

In [109]:
# Cleaning data to get rid of rows that have no values for either # of reviews

movie1 = movie.dropna(axis=0, subset=['num_user_for_reviews'])

user_votes = movie1['num_voted_users']
user_reviews = movie1['num_user_for_reviews']

corr, _ = pearsonr(user_votes, user_reviews)
print('Correlation Between # of votes and written reviews: %.3f' % corr)

Correlation Between # of votes and written reviews: 0.798

So, looking at these results, there is still a high correlation between the number of votes and number of written reviews. This was expected. However, there is not a direct linear relationship (which would imply a correlation of 1) between these two variables. Therefore, it is still valid to place within our dataset.

Heteroskedasticity¶

Regressions are more powerful when they are homoskedastic. Homoskedasticity is an important assumption that we employ. In modern times, since the advent of Robust White standard errors, we can just make a regression table with White standard errors and the default standard error, just so we can see the difference.

If we only used default standard errors, then they would be too small for a heteroskedastic model (which we have). This is why we use White standard errors -- they help correct for heteroskedasticity in models that are not homoskedastic.

Below, when we do the regression, we will demonstrate both versions -- White Standard Error and Regular Standard Error.

Methodology/Empirical Model¶

For clarification, we will be running two regressions. One with default standard errors, and one with Robust White standard errors. Both can provide us with valuable information about how our data changes when accounting for heteroskedasticity.

              data=movie).fit(cov_type ='HC0')

Our thought process that we took when choosing our model was how we could accurately show the data and the best way to find a statistically significant relationship. First, we analyzed the relationship between IMDb score and the numerical variables (duration, number user for reviews, voted users) through scatterplots because scatterplots help visualize the data as well as if there’s any trend between the independent and dependent variables. We created dummy variables to cover any influence the none-numerical variables may have had. Since these variables aren’t numerical, we used box plots to find trends within IMDb scores compared to variables such as language and country. We believe that this approach to our models helps identify trends in the data in a clear way.

First, we used the duration variable to see if the length of the movie affects the IMDb score. We included this variable because it’s numerical and it’s possible that movie length has an effect on a movie - for example, if the movie is too long, the critic might get bored and give it a lower score, or if the movie is too short, the critic may feel unsatisfied and also give it a lower score. Next, we used the number of voted users vs. IMDb score to see if the number of voters affect the IMDb score at all. Less voters on a particular movie would make each vote have greater weight in the final score, whereas the opposite would happen for a movie with lots of votes. We were interested to see how this numerical difference affects ratings. Third, we used the number of reviews vs IMDb score. This reasoning for using this variable is similar to the reasons we had for using the number of voted users vs. IMDb score, but there is a difference in voting and reviews in that voting just submits a rating out of 5 stars while reviews require a person to write their thoughts about the movie. We were interested to see if the number of reviews has any impact on the IMDb score because more reviews could mean that either the movie was very good or bad that it motivated more people to write about it. For our first dummy variables, we used language. Language has a possible effect on IMDb because higher ratings could be applied to Western and English movies. We believe this due to the fact that much of the film industry is dominated by white people and so far in history, critics have not been as receptive to movies that are not English (as seen as Parasite being the first non-English movie to win an Oscar, which was only recently). Our second dummy variable was the country the movie was made in. We applied similar logic from using the language variable to the country variable. We also wanted to account for possible outliers in our data based on countries that produce a majority or a minority of movies analyzed.

The director name variable could be important but we decided not to include it. This is because a celebrity director could have an impact on IMDb scores based on awareness alone, whereas a no-name director would garner less attraction around their movie and thus, less ratings to contribute to their IMDb score. We decided not to include this variable because it is hard to measure and it’s hard to quantify the impact of a person.

Looking here, it seems that while the standard errors were definitely higher with White Standard Errors, it does not affect any of the actual coefficients, nor does it make the p-value high enough to actually be put in doubt. In fact, all of our coefficients' p-values are below 0.01, so we can decisively comment upon our results.

Results¶

Overall, throughout the regressions, it was clear that neither the number of reviews or the number of ratings in general was associated with creating a difference in the numerical IMDb scores. The coeffecient is 0.000 for num_voted_users and num_user_for_reviews, making this completely moot in terms of having an effect or association on the overall score.

Duration has an extremely slight but, ultimately, negligible positive correlation with scores throughout all specifications of regressions we did. The coefficients were all less than 0.01, and with a rating system that goes from 0 to 10, this is a forgettable difference in scores.

However, our dummy variables proved useful in finding some interesting results. Looking at regression #2, it seems that having a documentary is associated with a 1.045 point increase in IMDb rating. This is an interesting find, and demonstrates what genres people may associate with better filmaking and quality. Documentaries tend to be well-produced, which can help account for this difference.

Contradicting our initial hypothesis, it seems that English movies are associated with a -0.775 point change in rating. This indicates that English movies are rated worse overall compared to other language's movies. In our opinion, we feel that this is because only high-quality and renowned movies from other languages even make it onto IMDB, whereas any regular English-dialogue movie can make it to IMDb. IMDb is an English-speaking website, and the internet has generally more exposure to the English-speaking world. Movies from other languages have higher barriers to surmount to make it onto IMDb -- this is not the case for English movies.

With English movies from the USA, we can see which of "USA" or "English" is the bigger factor in the lower scores -- through this regression it seems that it is the "English" portion, associated with a 0.593 decrease in score, as opposed to just "USA", the coefficient of which is -0.231.

In the final regression, similar results hold from prior regressions. An IMDb film being a documentary was associated with a ~ 1 point increase, with the "English" and "USA" coefficients displaying similarly negative values.

Conclusion¶

Our study tried to identify a relationship between the number of votes and reviews and the duration of a movie with the movie’s IMDb score. We did this through running 6 regressions with each regression having a different combination of variables. We also inserted dummy variables. Our results showed that only our dummy variables had some sort of effect, because the duration and number of votes and reviews didn’t seem to have an effect at all, and their coefficients were close to zero. In the future, we recommend a data set with more quantitative variables and a data set without distinct genres so we could also filter by genre. A shortcoming of our data set is that there is no column that shows whether the actresses are male or female, which would have been interesting to see if gender has an effect on rating as well, which is a shortcoming that could be circumvented by adding a gender column.
